{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6576251f-4b8c-4164-a9a6-e20827a6ad22","content":"## What happened\n\nApple's cryptographic frameworks (`Security.framework` / `CryptoKit`) have **never natively supported DSA**. In older .NET versions, `DSA.Create()` on macOS worked via a managed/OpenSSL-backed fallback. **.NET 11 removed that fallback**, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS (and iOS/tvOS).\n\nThis is part of .NET's long-running deprecation of DSA — the algorithm itself is considered legacy (FIPS 186-4 recommended transition away from it).\n\n## How to fix it\n\nYou have two options:\n\n### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended if you must keep verifying legacy signatures)\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.OpenSsl;\n\n// Load the public key\nusing var reader = new StreamReader(\"legacy-dsa-public.pem\");\nvar pemReader = new PemReader(reader);\nvar pubKey = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)pemReader.ReadObject();\n\n// Verify the signature\nvar signer = new DsaSigner();\nsigner.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);\n// DsaSigner.VerifySignature(message_hash, r, s)\nbool valid = signer.VerifySignature(hash, r, s);\n```\n\nBouncyCastle is a pure managed implementation — it runs on **every** .NET platform with no native dependency.\n\n### Option 2 — Migrate to a modern algorithm\n\nIf you control both signing and verification, migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** (`EdDSA`), which are supported on all platforms:\n\n```csharp\nusing var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);\nbool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);\n```\n\n### Summary\n\n| Approach | Effort | Long-term |\n|---|---|---|\n| BouncyCastle | Low — drop-in replacement | Keeps legacy DSA working everywhere |\n| Migrate to ECDSA/Ed25519 | Higher — re-sign or dual-verify | Best long-term solution |\n\nIf you only need to **verify** existing signatures during a transition period, BouncyCastle is the pragmatic choice. For new work, use ECDSA or Ed25519.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"97f0632a-53bc-4238-9463-47682ab8229d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue related to DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me provide what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7+, Apple's macOS deprecated DSA in their security frameworks, and .NET eventually removed support for DSA on macOS. Specifically, in .NET 7, `DSA.Create()` on macOS started throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException` because Apple removed DSA support from their cryptographic libraries (CommonCrypto/Security.framework).\n\n\nI should clarify the timeline here—DSA support on macOS has been a long-standing issue. Historically, .NET relied on OpenSSL through a shim library to support DSA on macOS since Apple's native frameworks didn't include it, but the platform has been gradually moving away from older cryptographic algorithms. `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because Apple's native cryptographic frameworks don't support DSA, and .NET removed the OpenSSL fallback that previously enabled it. To work around this, I could use a cross-platform library if only verifying legacy signatures rather than creating new ones. The user might be asking about a hypothetical scenario or there could be nuances in how DSA support evolved across versions. Regardless of the exact version boundary, the core issue remains the same—macOS lacks native DSA support, and .NET eventually removed its managed implementation, causing `DSA.Create()` to throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`. I'll focus on providing practical solutions for migrating away from DSA or working around the limitation.","outputTokens":1725,"requestId":"6811:3FDA7D:10820FA:14D81A3:69FFE2E5"},"id":"00d0ef7f-9688-481e-a71a-9051007948fb","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:44:40.860Z","parentId":"0b5c6f71-f486-44e2-92ef-161a764a859c"}
